268
00:17:42,080 --> 00:17:43,080
Nathan, wait.
Listen.

269
00:17:43,080 --> 00:17:44,680
I have something to show you,

270
00:17:44,680 --> 00:17:47,479
I just don't know if you'll be able
to handle it, that's all.

271
00:17:47,479 --> 00:17:50,039
I'm fed up with your mysteries.
I'm tired.

272
00:17:50,039 --> 00:17:52,118
Nathan, it'll take
five minutes of your time,

273
00:17:52,118 --> 00:17:54,038
no more.
And then I'm out of here.

274
00:17:54,038 --> 00:17:56,597
You'll never see me again.
I give you my word.

275
00:17:56,597 --> 00:17:59,117
- You give me your word?
- Yes.

276
00:17:59,157 --> 00:18:01,156
I give you my word.
You know who I am,

277
00:18:01,156 --> 00:18:03,155
you know where I work,
you're a lawyer.

278
00:18:03,155 --> 00:18:06,355
If I do anything wrong,
anything at all which...

279
00:18:06,355 --> 00:18:10,114
It wouldn't take you five minutes
to blow my career out of the water.

280
00:18:10,114 --> 00:18:13,073
Nathan, believe me,
it's important.

281
00:18:13,073 --> 00:18:14,273
You have to see it.

282
00:18:14,273 --> 00:18:16,712
I swear.

283
00:18:16,712 --> 00:18:20,312
It's important.
Come with me.

284
00:18:22,191 --> 00:18:25,150
Five minutes.
10 minutes... no more.

285
00:18:25,150 --> 00:18:27,991
And then... I'm gone.

286
00:18:34,549 --> 00:18:37,308
You brought me here
just to tell me this?

287
00:18:37,308 --> 00:18:38,468
What the hell does it mean?

288
00:18:38,468 --> 00:18:40,428
Or is that all part of the message?

289
00:18:40,428 --> 00:18:42,468
You come out with these
little riddles of yours

290
00:18:42,468 --> 00:18:44,707
and expect me to...

291
00:18:44,707 --> 00:18:47,786
You see that guy,
the kid in the orange jacket?

292
00:18:47,786 --> 00:18:48,866
Do you see him?

293
00:18:48,866 --> 00:18:50,825
Yeah, I see him.
So what?

294
00:18:50,825 --> 00:18:53,505
Name of Dennis.
10 years ago to this day,

295
00:18:53,505 --> 00:18:54,904
his father died here.

296
00:18:54,904 --> 00:18:58,864
He was waiting for a train
as he did every evening.

297
00:18:58,864 --> 00:19:01,623
He had a good job, happy family.

298
00:19:01,623 --> 00:19:05,742
And one evening, he'd had enough.

299
00:19:05,742 --> 00:19:08,301
And when the express came by,
he jumped.

300
00:19:08,301 --> 00:19:10,461
Was he a friend of yours?

301
00:19:10,461 --> 00:19:12,101
And these last few days,

302
00:19:12,101 --> 00:19:14,701
Dennis has come here
every evening.

303
00:19:14,701 --> 00:19:17,020
- Every evening.
- Do you ever answer a question?

304
00:19:17,020 --> 00:19:18,900
Look at him.

305
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:20,820
- Why should I?
- Look at him.

306
00:19:20,820 --> 00:19:24,379
Because in about two minutes,

307
00:19:24,379 --> 00:19:28,258
Dennis there will be dead.

308
00:19:28,258 --> 00:19:30,138
What the f...

309
00:19:36,696 --> 00:19:37,816
You're crazy.

310
00:19:37,816 --> 00:19:40,575
Completely crazy.

311
00:19:57,651 --> 00:20:01,252
You gotta take the Chambers Street Exit,
right across the platform.

312
00:20:18,087 --> 00:20:19,287
Look!

313
00:20:19,287 --> 00:20:20,447
He's got a gun!

314
00:20:20,447 --> 00:20:23,246
He's got a gun!
He's got a gun!

315
00:20:23,246 --> 00:20:25,246
Listen, don't do it!

316
00:20:25,246 --> 00:20:27,285
Please,
put the gun down!

317
00:22:00,065 --> 00:22:02,185
Is this your first time?

318
00:22:02,984 --> 00:22:06,664
You seem kind of young.

319
00:22:09,703 --> 00:22:11,223
He's here to see Dr. Kay.

320
00:22:11,223 --> 00:22:13,663
- Okay.
- He'll come get you in the day room.

321
00:22:13,663 --> 00:22:15,063
- This way?
- Mm-hmm.

322
00:22:15,063 --> 00:22:18,461
I... I think what you're
doing is wonderful.

323
00:22:50,574 --> 00:22:53,214
You came to see him?

324
00:22:53,574 --> 00:22:57,213
He'll be here.
Just have to wait.

325
00:22:59,693 --> 00:23:02,132
Come here.

326
00:23:03,652 --> 00:23:05,692
Come here.

327
00:23:05,692 --> 00:23:08,131
What's the matter?

328
00:23:08,171 --> 00:23:10,611
Something wrong?

329
00:23:13,411 --> 00:23:16,850
Myocardial metastases.

330
00:23:17,089 --> 00:23:18,529
Cancer of the heart muscle.

331
00:23:18,529 --> 00:23:21,049
Super rare, right?

332
00:23:21,409 --> 00:23:23,768
They wrote an article
about me in a magazine.

333
00:23:23,768 --> 00:23:26,367
It's in my room,
if you want to see it.

334
00:23:26,367 --> 00:23:32,366
Apparently, I could croak
from one day to the next...

335
00:23:32,366 --> 00:23:36,725
from one minute to the next.

336
00:23:37,605 --> 00:23:40,964
- Jeremy.
- Nathan.

337
00:23:40,964 --> 00:23:42,364
What do you do, Nathan?

338
00:23:42,364 --> 00:23:45,243
I'm a lawyer. Do you know
if he's going to be long?

339
00:23:45,243 --> 00:23:49,922
The first doc I saw,
you know what he called it?

340
00:23:50,042 --> 00:23:52,761
"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy".

341
00:23:52,761 --> 00:23:54,561
Wow.

342
00:23:54,561 --> 00:23:57,722
Can you believe that guy?

343
00:23:58,881 --> 00:24:01,241
You and me,

344
00:24:01,241 --> 00:24:02,880
we're gonna slap that...
that son-of-a-bitch with a lawsuit.

345
00:24:02,880 --> 00:24:03,960
What do you say?

346
00:24:03,960 --> 00:24:06,119
Legally, that's not exactly my bag.

347
00:24:06,119 --> 00:24:07,679
Jeremy, hello.

348
00:24:07,679 --> 00:24:10,318
- Up already?
- Yeah.

349
00:24:10,318 --> 00:24:12,758
- Happy birthday.
- Yeah, thanks.

350
00:24:12,758 --> 00:24:15,397
You've made a new friend.

351
00:24:15,397 --> 00:24:18,156
- Are you the new volunteer?
- He's a lawyer.

352
00:24:18,196 --> 00:24:20,116
He and I are gonna throw
a doctor's ass in the slammer.

353
00:24:20,116 --> 00:24:24,675
Oh, well... see you later.

354
00:24:25,115 --> 00:24:27,114
Bye.

355
00:24:32,593 --> 00:24:35,313
You smell that stink?

356
00:24:36,112 --> 00:24:37,831
Like something's rotting?

357
00:24:37,831 --> 00:24:39,992
Behind the stink of detergent...

358
00:24:39,992 --> 00:24:42,391
can't you smell that?

359
00:24:42,831 --> 00:24:45,711
It reeks of death around here.

360
00:24:45,711 --> 00:24:49,030
Why do you think
she puts up with it?

361
00:24:49,550 --> 00:24:53,749
She had a kid who died.
That's why.

362
00:24:54,469 --> 00:24:58,948
All of us in here
are going out in body bags,

363
00:24:58,948 --> 00:25:01,107
and she knows that.

364
00:25:01,988 --> 00:25:06,146
She thinks that when we see
her little darling up there...

365
00:25:06,263 --> 00:25:07,783
we'll tell him
how mommy's doing.

366
00:25:07,783 --> 00:25:09,503
And we'll take care of him.

367
00:25:09,503 --> 00:25:13,823
Make sure he eats his dinner
and goes to the potty up in Heaven.

368
00:25:13,823 --> 00:25:16,382
Volunteer, my ass.

369
00:25:16,382 --> 00:25:17,981
What about you?

370
00:25:17,981 --> 00:25:19,902
You got a message to send, too?

371
00:25:19,902 --> 00:25:22,181
Who you got up there, huh?

372
00:25:22,861 --> 00:25:26,620
I'm going soon,
so make the most of it.

373
00:25:27,261 --> 00:25:29,620
Some "dearly beloved?"

374
00:25:29,620 --> 00:25:31,459
- Or maybe...
- Excuse me.

375
00:25:31,459 --> 00:25:32,939
Hey!

376
00:25:32,939 --> 00:25:34,139
Hey, come back.

377
00:25:34,139 --> 00:25:37,458
I didn't mean it like that.

378
00:25:45,338 --> 00:25:48,537
I don't know how to die.

379
00:25:48,537 --> 00:25:51,257
None of us know how to die.

380
00:25:52,537 --> 00:25:56,176
But maybe...

381
00:25:56,176 --> 00:25:59,095
somewhere deep inside of us...

382
00:25:59,095 --> 00:26:00,815
a part of us does know how.

383
00:26:00,815 --> 00:26:05,814
Maybe it's not as terrible
as it seems.

384
00:26:05,814 --> 00:26:08,854
Try and rest.

385
00:26:09,334 --> 00:26:11,134
You know, Nathan,
the dying have taught me one thing...

386
00:26:11,134 --> 00:26:14,533
You know, Nathan,
the dying have taught me one thing...

387
00:26:14,533 --> 00:26:17,612
that you can look death in the face
and go on living.

388
00:26:17,612 --> 00:26:20,052
Our mission here is
to keep them company.

389
00:26:20,052 --> 00:26:22,492
Keep company with those
about to die

390
00:26:22,492 --> 00:26:24,532
so that they can depart in peace.

391
00:26:24,532 --> 00:26:27,091
Great, but what's it
got to do with me?

392
00:26:27,091 --> 00:26:28,212
Me, my.

393
00:26:28,212 --> 00:26:29,731
My little consciousness,

394
00:26:29,731 --> 00:26:32,370
my little comforts,
my little life.

395
00:26:32,370 --> 00:26:36,530
What about others, Nathan,
do you ever think about them?

396
00:26:36,530 --> 00:26:39,729
And Dennis?
Have you thought about Dennis?

397
00:26:39,729 --> 00:26:41,769
If you knew he was going
to blow his brains out,

398
00:26:41,769 --> 00:26:42,928
why didn't you do something?

399
00:26:42,928 --> 00:26:45,328
Why didn't you try to listen to him?

400
00:26:45,328 --> 00:26:47,569
Who kept Dennis company
so he'd "depart in peace?"

401
00:26:47,569 --> 00:26:50,888
Anyway, how did you know
he was going to die?

402
00:26:50,928 --> 00:26:52,647
This time I want an answer,
none of your...

403
00:26:52,687 --> 00:26:54,287
- I saw it.
- You saw it?

404
00:26:54,287 --> 00:26:55,687
- Yes.
- How did you see it?

405
00:26:55,727 --> 00:26:57,606
Was it written on his face?

406
00:26:57,606 --> 00:27:00,046
- Yes.
- Yes?

407
00:27:00,046 --> 00:27:02,966
Listen, I'm beat.
I didn't sleep last night because of you,

408
00:27:02,966 --> 00:27:05,405
- and I've got to be at work...
- Nathan,

409
00:27:05,405 --> 00:27:06,485
people who come here,

410
00:27:06,485 --> 00:27:09,645
they've already traveled
a long road

411
00:27:09,645 --> 00:27:11,405
paved with suffering.

412
00:27:11,405 --> 00:27:15,044
But they have had time
to prepare themselves.

413
00:27:15,404 --> 00:27:17,564
But often death comes...

414
00:27:17,564 --> 00:27:19,643
unexpectedly.
It can't be predicted.

415
00:27:19,643 --> 00:27:20,803
Yes, I know, yes.

416
00:27:20,803 --> 00:27:24,442
For instance, say you cross
the street at the wrong moment,

417
00:27:24,442 --> 00:27:27,482
or the body just gives out...
just like that.

418
00:27:27,482 --> 00:27:29,201
Snap your fingers,
you're dead.

419
00:27:29,201 --> 00:27:30,641
We see that every day.

420
00:27:30,641 --> 00:27:33,962
And those people never have
time to untangle the knots.

421
00:27:33,962 --> 00:27:36,961
They never have time
to prepare themselves.

422
00:27:36,961 --> 00:27:38,040
And so?

423
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:40,840
And so...

424
00:27:41,080 --> 00:27:44,640
the role of the Messengers
is to give those people too

425
00:27:44,640 --> 00:27:47,039
a chance to be reconciled.

426
00:27:47,079 --> 00:27:50,038
- "The Messengers?"
- Yes.

427
00:27:53,958 --> 00:27:55,678
I don't understand.

428
00:27:55,678 --> 00:27:58,477
There are people out there
who know in advance

429
00:27:58,477 --> 00:28:00,558
that someone is going to die.

430
00:28:00,558 --> 00:28:03,276
Let's say they...
"got the message".

431
00:28:03,276 --> 00:28:05,157
And in those cases,

432
00:28:05,157 --> 00:28:09,636
their job is to help that person
depart in peace... reconcile.

433
00:28:09,636 --> 00:28:11,995
- And you're one of these "Messengers?"
- Yes, I am.

434
00:28:12,035 --> 00:28:13,755
- You know who's going to die?
- Yes.

435
00:28:13,755 --> 00:28:15,675
- You see it?
- Yes, I see it.

436
00:28:15,675 --> 00:28:18,715
And you help them depart in peace.

437
00:28:18,995 --> 00:28:21,994
Nathan, I realize it
may be hard to believe...

438
00:28:21,994 --> 00:28:25,154
But Dennis didn't depart in peace.

439
00:28:25,393 --> 00:28:26,713
- No.
- Why?

440
00:28:26,713 --> 00:28:29,433
We don't always succeed.
Sometimes we get there too late.

441
00:28:29,433 --> 00:28:31,672
No one has power over
the hour of death.

442
00:28:31,672 --> 00:28:33,393
No one.

443
00:28:33,752 --> 00:28:35,712
I don't believe you.

444
00:28:35,712 --> 00:28:37,792
Have it your way, Nathan.

445
00:28:37,792 --> 00:28:39,672
But these things can still exist

446
00:28:39,672 --> 00:28:42,431
whether you believe
in them or not.

447
00:28:42,671 --> 00:28:45,950
I know when someone's
going to die... I see it.

448
00:28:45,950 --> 00:28:50,590
And I make every effort
to prepare them for what's coming.

449
00:28:50,710 --> 00:28:53,389
Well, I think I've
heard enough for today.

450
00:29:16,666 --> 00:29:19,746
What exactly are you
trying to tell me?

451
00:29:20,265 --> 00:29:24,265
Are you trying to tell me
I'm going to die soon? Is that it?

452
00:29:24,265 --> 00:29:28,304
I told you everything.
You know everything.

453
00:29:28,304 --> 00:29:30,704
Go fuck yourself.

454
00:29:49,581 --> 00:29:51,021
Hurry up.

455
00:29:51,021 --> 00:29:54,660
Sam.
Sam, hurry up.

456
00:29:54,860 --> 00:29:57,140
Bring that over.
Hurry up.

457
00:29:57,140 --> 00:29:58,380
Breathe, breathe,
breathe.

458
00:29:58,380 --> 00:30:02,419
We need a neck brace and a splint.
Get that here.

459
00:31:11,729 --> 00:31:14,968
Look straight into the light.

460
00:31:14,968 --> 00:31:16,808
Don't move.

461
00:32:01,842 --> 00:32:03,601
The smell of the ghosts.

462
00:32:03,601 --> 00:32:06,481
Follow the smell of the ghosts
and you'll find the flower.

463
00:32:06,481 --> 00:32:08,760
What did you say, sweetheart?

464
00:32:08,760 --> 00:32:10,000
It's a cactus.

465
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:12,440
It makes a flower once a year,
at midnight.

466
00:32:12,440 --> 00:32:13,960
Only once.

467
00:32:13,960 --> 00:32:16,879
At 12:00 noon, the flower dies,
and it smells like ghosts.

468
00:32:16,879 --> 00:32:18,799
The flower smells like ghosts?

469
00:32:18,799 --> 00:32:19,919
Yeah,
but it's real nice.

470
00:32:19,919 --> 00:32:21,838
Mommy says ghosts smell good.

471
00:32:21,838 --> 00:32:24,158
The Night Blooming Cereus.
Yes, I remember.

472
00:32:24,158 --> 00:32:25,798
Mommy told me about it too.

473
00:32:25,798 --> 00:32:27,917
An Indian legend.

474
00:32:27,917 --> 00:32:29,717
Honey, can I talk to Mommy?

475
00:32:29,717 --> 00:32:32,237
She says she'll call you back.

476
00:32:32,237 --> 00:32:34,476
Tracey?

477
00:32:34,476 --> 00:32:36,796
Hello?

478
00:32:40,596 --> 00:32:42,675
I had everything checked out,
everything...

479
00:32:42,675 --> 00:32:45,355
brain, heart, lungs, blood.

480
00:32:45,355 --> 00:32:47,754
I got my urine tested,
my saliva, my sperm...

481
00:32:47,754 --> 00:32:49,354
they tested everything

482
00:32:49,354 --> 00:32:50,594
and they found nothing.

483
00:32:50,594 --> 00:32:52,273
Nothing at all.
There's the file.

484
00:32:52,273 --> 00:32:53,593
Take a look.

485
00:32:53,593 --> 00:32:55,793
A little hypoglycemia
and nothing else.

486
00:32:55,793 --> 00:32:57,713
Nothing else at all.

487
00:32:58,272 --> 00:32:59,873
I'm very glad to hear that, Nathan.

488
00:32:59,873 --> 00:33:01,712
- I'm happy for you.
- So as of this minute,

489
00:33:01,712 --> 00:33:02,992
you are out of my life.

490
00:33:02,992 --> 00:33:05,112
No phone calls,
no visits, nothing.

491
00:33:05,112 --> 00:33:07,951
If I ever see you again
here or any place at all,

492
00:33:07,951 --> 00:33:09,631
it'll mean the police...
got it?

493
00:33:09,631 --> 00:33:11,151
May I show you something?

494
00:33:11,151 --> 00:33:13,870
- No.
- It's a photograph.

495
00:33:14,230 --> 00:33:16,390
Anna Rachevsky.

496
00:33:16,390 --> 00:33:17,750
Very cute.
Now leave.

497
00:33:17,750 --> 00:33:19,230
From a Russian family.

498
00:33:19,230 --> 00:33:22,390
That photograph was taken
the day she arrived in New York.

499
00:33:22,390 --> 00:33:24,709
I don't give a shit.

500
00:33:24,709 --> 00:33:26,749
Not much money,
father out of the picture.

501
00:33:26,749 --> 00:33:29,148
She wanted to go to college,
but the closest she ever got

502
00:33:29,148 --> 00:33:32,307
was working in
the cafeteria at NYU.

503
00:33:32,347 --> 00:33:34,707
Her boss treated her
like an animal.

504
00:33:34,707 --> 00:33:37,267
The students didn't even notice.

505
00:33:37,547 --> 00:33:38,627
Except one.

506
00:33:38,627 --> 00:33:41,946
He was a foreigner too...

507
00:33:42,026 --> 00:33:44,066
a Frenchman.

508
00:33:44,226 --> 00:33:46,945
She welcomed the kindness
he showed her.

509
00:33:46,945 --> 00:33:48,705
But later, she was fired.

510
00:33:48,705 --> 00:33:51,225
He lost touch with her.

511
00:33:51,225 --> 00:33:53,344
End of story.

512
00:33:55,424 --> 00:33:57,984
Anna Rachevsky, right.

513
00:33:57,984 --> 00:33:59,704
- Coming back?
- Yes.

514
00:33:59,704 --> 00:34:03,143
She works at the Greenwind diner
in Queens.

515
00:34:03,143 --> 00:34:04,223
Late night shift.

516
00:34:04,223 --> 00:34:06,462
Not very well paying.

517
00:34:06,462 --> 00:34:10,022
She's had a child...
a son.

518
00:34:10,302 --> 00:34:12,381
You should stop by and see her.

519
00:34:12,381 --> 00:34:15,181
I'm sure she would
enjoy that very much.

520
00:34:15,181 --> 00:34:17,021
I'll do that, maybe, yes.

521
00:34:17,021 --> 00:34:18,981
Good.

522
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:21,901
What?

523
00:34:22,380 --> 00:34:24,100
Have you understood me?

524
00:34:24,100 --> 00:34:26,340
No.

525
00:34:26,820 --> 00:34:28,499
What?

526
00:34:28,499 --> 00:34:30,019
What was it this time?
